'''Édouard Chambon''' ([[Valence, Drôme|Valence]]), is a French software engineer who was world record holder for fastest single time on a 3x3x3 [[Rubik's Cube]] with a time of 9.18 seconds and fastest average time of 11.48 seconds.<ref>[http://www.ladepeche.fr/article/2008/09/19/476468-rubik-cube-jean-pons-quete-nouvelle-couronne-europeenne.html Rubik's Cube. Jean Pons en quête d'une nouvelle couronne européenne] 2008 "En Espagne où 150 concurrents s'affronteront, dont son vieil adversaire français Édouard Chambon,"</ref> These records were set at the Murcia Open February 23, 2008.<ref name="WCA">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcubeassociation.org/results/p.php?i=2004CHAM01|title=Official results of Edouard Chambon|accessdate=2008-02-24|work=worldcubeassociation.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.speedcubing.com/records/recs_cube_333.html|title=Rubik's Cube 3x3x3: Fastest Time to Solve|accessdate=2007-03-26|work=SpeedCubing.com}}</ref><ref>[http://www.lexpress.fr/actualites/1/actualite/championnat-de-france-de-rubik-s-cube-kanneti-sae-han-conserve-son-titre_985842.html Championnat de France de Rubik's Cube  Kanneti Sae Han conserve son titre]  23/04/2011 "Edouard Chambon, un ingénieur de 25 ans, originaire de Valence, a pris la seconde place avec 11.65 secondes, parmi les meilleures performances de cet ancien titré national."</ref>

Chambon won the 3x3x3 Rubik's Cube event at the 2005 French Open,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lerubikscube.com/passion-speedcubing/|title=Personal Biography of his competitions experience}}</ref> in what was only his second tournament. In the first round of this tournament, he broke the European Record for the fastest average time. Later that year he finished second in the World Championships.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hasbro.com/media/pl/page.release/dn/default.cfm?release=408|title=Jean Pons of France Crowned As 2005 World Rubik’s Cube Champion|accessdate=2007-03-26|work=Hasbro.com |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070223082442/http://www.hasbro.com/media/pl/page.release/dn/default.cfm?release=408 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-02-23}}</ref> A series of top-four finishes followed before he broke the World Record for the fastest solve at the Belgian Open in 2007. Chambon broke the world record in the first round with a 10.36 seconds solve. However, he was then beaten by Thibaut Jacquinot in the final. In 2008, he regained his world record with a time of 9.18 seconds. His record was broken again by [[Yu Nakajima]], who set an average of 11.28 seconds and a best time of 8.72 on May 4, 2008 at Kawashi Open 2008.

